page.title: 01Lincolnshire Wolds S/w Louth
page.content: Most of the block is more than 75 metres above sea level, rising to 136m in SW corner. It forms part of the central section of Lincolnshire Wols, a chalk upland region and consists predominantly of arable land, divided into relatively large fields, some measuring 100ha or more in area, with few hedges and only isolated clumps of trees. the only watercourses are a stream flowing from centre of block in NE direction to join another flowing NW. The block is interesected by one main road an two minor roads, all leading in NE/SW direction. At extreme eastern edge is part of village of Tathwell, while hamlet of Withcall is located in NW Corner. Elsewhere there are only few isolated houses and farms. Population density is under 2 per ha. The only employment within this block is farming, present
